CONSULT-28-G — Near-plane (w-plane) clipping spec: D3D9 vs D3D11
Why near-w geometry renders bounded under D3D9 but explodes into radial shards under D3D11

Author: GPU rasterization-spec consult (Opus 4.8)
Date: 2026-06-07
Confidence legend: [HIGH] spec-cited verbatim / [MED] strong inference from spec + corroborating sources / [LOW] plausible, needs runtime confirmation

=====================================================================
EXECUTIVE ANSWER (read this first)
=====================================================================

The pixels-to-infinity / radial-shards symptom is the canonical signature of a
triangle that has a vertex with w <= 0 (or w ~ +epsilon) which is NOT being
clipped against the near/w plane before the perspective divide. After
divide-by-w, (x/w, y/w) for a near-zero or negative w explodes to +/-huge NDC,
and the rasterizer draws a triangle edge sweeping across the whole screen
(the "shard"). [HIGH — this is the textbook divide-by-tiny-w failure]

BOTH D3D9 and D3D11 *specify* mandatory "0 < w" clipping. So if the spec were
the whole story, neither would explode. The fact that D3D9 renders the same
mesh bounded and D3D11 explodes means the near/w clip is effectively NOT
happening on the D3D11 path in this port. The single most likely reason
(ranked in section 5) is NOT a difference in the documented clip algorithm but
a difference in WHICH path produces SV_Position and whether the projection it
emits actually yields a sane sign/magnitude of w — i.e. the bug is upstream of
the rasterizer (the VS / WVP it feeds), and D3D9's fixed-function or T&L clip
stage was masking a projection that already had degenerate w. (See section 5.)

=====================================================================
1. NEAR-PLANE (w-PLANE) CLIPPING — WHEN/HOW IT HAPPENS
=====================================================================

Both APIs clip in homogeneous clip space, *after* the vertex shader emits
SV_Position and *before* the perspective divide. The canonical clip volume
(D3D convention, z in [0,w]) is:

    0 < w
    -w <= x <= w   (or wider, if a guard band is used — see section 2)
    -w <= y <= w   (or wider, if a guard band is used)
    0 <= z <= w

Source — D3D11_RASTERIZER_DESC, DepthClipEnable member, verbatim:
"The hardware always performs x and y clipping of rasterized coordinates. When
DepthClipEnable is set to the default - TRUE, the hardware also clips the z
value (that is, the hardware performs the last step of the following
algorithm).
    0 < w
    -w <= x <= w (or arbitrarily wider range if implementation uses a guard
                  band to reduce clipping burden)
    -w <= y <= w (or arbitrarily wider range ...)
    0 <= z <= w
When you set DepthClipEnable to FALSE, the hardware skips the z clipping ...
However, the hardware still performs the '0 < w' clipping."
[HIGH] https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/api/d3d11/ns-d3d11-d3d11_rasterizer_desc

Key consequence: the "0 < w" plane is the near/w clip. It is listed as
mandatory and is NOT gated by DepthClipEnable. So in spec terms, a D3D11
triangle with one vertex at w<=0 and two at w>0 is supposed to be CLIPPED to
the w>0 boundary — the offending vertex is replaced by new vertices generated
on the near/w plane, attributes interpolated, and the result is a BOUNDED
polygon. It should never reach rasterization with a w<=0 vertex intact.
[HIGH for the spec; the open question is whether the runtime path you built
actually exercises this — see section 5.]

What "escape" looks like: if a vertex with w ~ 0+ (tiny positive) survives
clipping (it passes 0<w because it is technically positive), then x/w and y/w
become enormous but FINITE. The guard band (section 2) determines whether that
enormous-but-finite projected triangle is then clipped/discarded or rasterized
as a shard. This is the realistic failure mode for "w slightly positive":
it passes the 0<w test, projects huge, and if it also slips past the guard
band it rasterizes as a shard. [MED]

D3D9 fixed-function / T&L vs programmable — the historical difference:
- In the D3D9 fixed-function and software/hardware T&L pipeline, Direct3D's own
  clipper runs as a defined pipeline stage and clips primitives to the frustum
  (including the near plane) for vertices it transforms, controlled by
  D3DRS_CLIPPING (default TRUE). [HIGH]
  https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/direct3d9/primitive-clipping-state
- For a programmable VS (vs_x_x) the GPU still performs frustum/near clipping in
  hardware — but the practical point is that D3D9 + its drivers leaned on a
  generously-sized guard band AND a mandatory near clip, and the D3D9 reference
  rasterizer was conservative about near-w. [MED]

=====================================================================
2. GUARD BAND & VIEWPORT
=====================================================================

Guard band = a rectangle in screen/NDC space POTENTIALLY MUCH LARGER than the
viewport, to which the clipper clips X and Y instead of clipping to the
viewport itself. Triangles fully inside the guard band but outside the viewport
are accepted and trim-rasterized (pixels outside the viewport/scissor are
dropped) rather than geometrically clipped — this avoids generating new
vertices. Triangles that exceed the guard band trigger true geometric clipping.
Source (driver docs, verbatim):
"A guard band is a rectangle that is potentially larger than the viewport (and
even the render target), to which vertices can be clipped automatically by the
driver. The Microsoft Direct3D clipping code clips to this rectangle instead of
to the viewport. By allowing the driver to specify potentially large guard band
rectangles, the need to generate new vertices due to clipping is reduced. One
example is a hardware device that can correctly render as long as screen x and y
coordinates fall in the range -2048 through 2047."
[HIGH] https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-hardware/drivers/display/guard-band-clipping

Critical clarification for the explosion question:
- The guard band is an X/Y optimization ONLY. The "0 < w" near clip is
  orthogonal and (per section 1) always runs. The guard band never lets a
  w<=0 vertex through; it only changes whether large *finite* X/Y projections
  are geometrically clipped or just pixel-trimmed. [HIGH inference from both
  specs: the D3D11 algorithm lists guard band as a widening of the X/Y rows
  only, with "0 < w" on its own un-widened row.]
- A vertex with tiny-positive w projects to a GIGANTIC but finite (x/w, y/w).
  That coordinate is far OUTSIDE any practical guard band (e.g. >> 2048 / >>
  32K depending on HW). So such a triangle SHOULD hit true geometric clipping
  and be bounded — UNLESS the projected magnitude overflows the rasterizer's
  fixed-point coordinate range and wraps/saturates, OR the clip is being
  skipped. The shard look is exactly an edge that swept to the fixed-point
  coordinate limit. [MED]

D3D9 guard band: exposed to the app via D3DCAPS9.GuardBandLeft/Top/Right/Bottom
(float), so D3D9 apps could test a mesh's screen-space bbox against the guard
band and skip subdividing/clipping. D3D9 drivers commonly advertised large
guard bands AND the Direct3D runtime clipper backed them up. The relevant
difference vs a naive D3D11 port is NOT "D3D9 had a bigger guard band" — it is
that D3D9 had a documented, on-by-default *runtime clipper* (D3DRS_CLIPPING,
ProcessVertices, CLIPTLVERTS) as a safety net for the transform stage. [MED]
https://developer.download.nvidia.com/assets/gamedev/docs/Guard_Band_Clipping.pdf
http://doc.51windows.net/directx9_sdk/graphics/reference/d3d/structures/d3dcaps9.htm

=====================================================================
3. D3DRS_CLIPPING / CLIP CONTROL — AND THE D3D11 EQUIVALENT
=====================================================================

D3D9:
- D3DRS_CLIPPING (default TRUE) enables/disables Direct3D's primitive clipping
  for geometry the pipeline transforms. [HIGH]
  https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/direct3d9/primitive-clipping-state
- D3DPMISCCAPS_CLIPTLVERTS (PrimitiveMiscCaps): if set, the device clips
  post-transformed (T&L) vertex data to Z and to the X/Y viewport extents. If
  NOT set, the *application* is responsible for clipping T&L vertices it sends.
  In software vertex processing the device is always capable of clipping T&L
  verts. [HIGH]
  https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-hardware/drivers/display/clipping-transformed-vertices
- Important nuance: Direct3D does NOT clip pre-transformed (XYZRHW / from a
  vertex buffer) vertices unless they come through ProcessVertices. So for
  fixed-function/T&L *model-space* geometry (the normal case), D3DRS_CLIPPING
  TRUE gives you a robust near-plane clip; for app-pretransformed verts you owe
  the clip yourself. [HIGH]

D3D11 equivalent:
- There is NO "D3DRS_CLIPPING on/off" master switch in D3D11. Frustum clipping
  in X/Y/W is implicit and mandatory (you cannot turn off the "0 < w" or X/Y
  clip). The ONLY app-facing clip toggle is
  D3D11_RASTERIZER_DESC.DepthClipEnable, which controls Z clipping only
  (default TRUE). [HIGH] (rasterizer_desc source above)
- Therefore a port CANNOT reproduce the explosion by "forgetting to enable
  D3D11 clipping" the way one might fear — X/Y/W clipping is not optional in
  D3D11. This means the shards are NOT caused by a missing D3DRS_CLIPPING
  analogue. (This rules OUT the most superficially-attractive hypothesis.)
  [HIGH — this is an important negative result for the investigation.]

=====================================================================
4. DepthClipEnable — WHAT IT ACTUALLY CLIPS
=====================================================================

DepthClipEnable clips Z, not W. Specifically it toggles only the final
"0 <= z <= w" row of the algorithm. With DepthClipEnable = TRUE (default),
geometry crossing the near/far DEPTH planes is depth-clipped. With it FALSE,
depth clipping is skipped (useful for stencil shadow volumes / skyboxes) but
"the hardware still performs the '0 < w' clipping." [HIGH] (rasterizer_desc)

Bottom line on Depth vs the near-w explosion: DepthClipEnable does NOT cause and
does NOT cure the near-w shard explosion. Even DepthClipEnable=FALSE keeps the
mandatory w>0 clip. The explosion is a W-space / projection problem, not a
Z-clip problem. Do not chase DepthClipEnable for this symptom. [HIGH]

=====================================================================
5. BOTTOM LINE — RANKED MOST-LIKELY SINGLE DIFFERENCE
=====================================================================

Because BOTH APIs mandate "0 < w" clipping, a true spec-conformant D3D11
rasterizer would also bound the mesh. The explosion therefore implies the
SV_Position w reaching the D3D11 clipper is degenerate in a way it was NOT on
the D3D9 path. Ranked causes:

RANK 1 [MED-HIGH] — The D3D11 VS emits a DIFFERENT (degenerate) w than the D3D9
path. Most likely a projection / WVP matrix issue: row-major vs column-major
mismatch, a missing transpose, or an un-fed/zero cbuffer producing w == 0 for
many vertices. Your codebase already has a documented D3D11 cbuffer-transpose
quirk (col-vec engine vs row-vec bytecode). If the WVP fed to a //asm-VS
fallback or a reauthored VS is transposed/zeroed, the .w (4th row dot) collapses
to ~0 for whole swaths of a mesh -> tiny/zero w -> divide explosion. This is the
single most probable real cause given the port context. The D3D9 fixed-function
/ T&L path computed w with the engine's known-good projection, so it stayed
sane. ACTION: capture SV_Position.w in RenderDoc for the exploding draw under
gl11 and compare to gl05; look for w ~ 0 or sign flips.

RANK 2 [MED] — The exploding geometry is fed through a path where the D3D9
client relied on the RUNTIME clipper (D3DRS_CLIPPING TRUE / ProcessVertices /
CLIPTLVERTS) to clip near-plane-straddling geometry, and the D3D11 port has no
equivalent runtime pre-clip. If the mesh is effectively pre-transformed
(XYZRHW-style, UI / billboards / sky) or the //asm-VS fallback bypasses proper
projection, the near-w vertices that D3D9's transform-stage clipper would have
trimmed now flow straight into the D3D11 rasterizer. Even though D3D11's HW
"0<w" should catch true w<=0, a w == +epsilon survivor projects huge and shards.
ACTION: identify whether the exploding mesh is the //asm-VS fallback geometry
(interiors/sky from the phase-19 work) or pretransformed UI.

RANK 3 [LOW-MED] — Tiny-positive-w survivors slipping past the guard band and
overflowing the rasterizer's fixed-point X/Y coordinate range, wrapping to the
opposite screen edge (classic "radial shard" wrap). This is a downstream
manifestation of RANK 1/2, not an independent root cause; fixing w fixes it.

RANK 4 [LOW] — A genuine half-open vs near-plane convention difference (D3D9
clipped at the near plane with a slightly different epsilon / the D3D9 REF
rasterizer was more conservative about near-w). Possible but weak; D3D11's
mandatory 0<w makes a pure convention gap an unlikely sole cause.

DEFINITELY-NOT (negative results, do not pursue):
- "Missing D3DRS_CLIPPING equivalent in D3D11" as a literal toggle — there is
  none; X/Y/W clipping is non-optional in D3D11. [HIGH]
- DepthClipEnable — clips Z only; irrelevant to the w explosion. [HIGH]
- Guard-band size differences — guard band is X/Y-only and never passes w<=0;
  not a root cause. [HIGH]

ONE-LINE VERDICT:
The shards are a w-space (perspective-divide) failure, almost certainly because
the D3D11 VS/WVP emits w ~ 0 (transpose/zeroed-cbuffer/projection bug) for
near-plane geometry that D3D9's fixed-function/T&L runtime clipper used to trim;
verify by reading SV_Position.w in a gl11-vs-gl05 RenderDoc capture of the
offending draw. Chase the projection/WVP feeding SV_Position, NOT DepthClipEnable
or any clip-enable toggle.

